{
  "content": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "A sonic history ",
          "textSize": "heading-one"
        }
      ],
      "align": "center"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Gasolina (2004) "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "",
          "textSize": "heading-three"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "textSize": "heading-three",
          "text": "Origin Narrative "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Puerto Rico 1990s "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "The established narrative situates reggaetón a form of artistic codemixing from Puerto Rico that emerged from the crossroads between Jamaican dancehall, New York hip-hop, and Afro-Panamanian "
        },
        {
          "text": "reggae en español. ",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": "The interplay between these genres was not linear, but rather simultaneous. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "reggae en español "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "meren-rap / merenhouse"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "bomba and plena"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "salsa"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "merengue"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "(Latin) hip-hop"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "reggae "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "textSize": "heading-three",
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "\"The snares suggest connections to a long history of "
        },
        {
          "text": "pistas",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": " and mixtaps which preceded the breakthrough pop smash and which remain as audible, palpable, if subtle remnants of an unbridled, underground, sample-based past in a genre that has since embraced slick synthesizers and commercial channels\" (Marshall, 2009 p. 21). "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "textSize": "heading-three",
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "horizontal-separator",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "textSize": "heading-three",
          "text": "Dem Bow "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "The predominant rhythmic orientation of reggaetón is derived directly from dancehall reggae. While there is also influence from roots reggae (à la Bob Marley), dancehall reggae's synthetic textures, tempos, rapid-fire rap, and minimalist focus on 3+3+2 cross rhythms demarcated by heavy, synthesized drums have had a stronger influence. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "riddim: a 4/4 pulse of kick drum and syncopated snares along a 3+3+2 groove. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "This can be heard in diverse Caribbean genres such as reggae, mento, soca, calypso, salsa, son, merengue, konpa, and zouk. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "bam bam riddims "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Dancehall's uptake in Panama and Puerto Rico was related to its counter-cultural connotations and close relationship with rap or hip-hop and thus sounds and images of modernity, urbanity, and Blackness. While roots reggae preached pan-African liberation, dancehall embraced more local concerns resonant with hip-hop: crime, drugs, violence, sex, poverty, corruption. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "\"Dancehall and hip-hop have tended to travel together, heard outside their principal sites of production as two sides of the same coin\" (Marshall, 2009 p. 25). Dancehall made its way to San Juan not from Kingston, but from New York. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "textSize": "heading-three",
          "text": "Luney Tunes "
        },
        {
          "text": "alternates the snares every four measures to create a subtle, stylistically grounded sense of movement against the otherwise repetitive structures of the track "
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "title": "A sonic guide to reggaetón's globalization ",
